==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nitre
<hw>Ni"tre</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>nitre</ets>, L. <ets>nitrum</ets> native
soda, natron, Gr. <?/; cf. Ar. <ets>nit⟦umac⟧n</ets>,
<ets>natr⟦umac⟧n</ets> natron. Cf. <er>Natron</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A white crystalline semitransparent salt;
potassium nitrate; saltpeter. See <er>Saltpeter</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Native sodium carbonate;
natron.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For though thou wash thee with <qex>niter</qex>, and take thee
much soap, yet thine iniquity is marked before me.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. ii.
22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cubic niter</b></col>, <cd>a deliquescent salt, sodium
nitrate, found as a native incrustation, like niter, in Peru and Chile,
whence it is known also as <altname>Chile saltpeter</altname>.</cd> --
<col><b>Niter bush</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a genus
(<gen>Nitraria</gen>) of thorny shrubs bearing edible berries, and
growing in the saline plains of Asia and Northern Africa.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nithing</ent>⟦br⟧

